When using the Stream handler, and setting a 'timeout' option, it is possible that the Guzzle client will not honour the timeout, but wait for the server to have finished sending the body.

In order to test this, I created a "reverse slowloris" php page on the target webserver which echoes a `.` char, calls `flush` then sleeps 500ms, for 5 seconds (and tested that it works as expected using the browser, as depending on the way php is integrated into the webserver there might be buffering at play, which has to be disabled). 

Then I created a Guzzle client, using just the StreamHandler, set to it a timeout of 2 seconds, and tested it against that page.

The end result is that the StreamHandler does not time-out. It waits for 5 seconds and reports happily a 200 OK response.

I think that this might be an upstream php bug - where the http stream wrapper does not honour the 'timeout' context option - at least for the case where the remote side does send a small chunk of data every N seconds, with N < $timeout.

After testing this, I looked at my own implementation of a php-streams based http client, in `phpxmlrpc/phpxmlrpc`, and, while that one is massively more dumb and totally not async, its code does show that a different approach was used in order to make the timeout work

```php
$fp = @stream_socket_client("$transport://$connectServer:$connectPort", $errno, $errstr, $connectTimeout, STREAM_CLIENT_CONNECT, $context);
if ($fp) {
    if ($opts['timeout'] > 0) {
        stream_set_timeout($fp, $opts['timeout'], 0);
    }
} else {
    ...
}

if (!fputs($fp, $op, strlen($op))) {
...
}

$info = stream_get_meta_data($fp);
if ($info['timed_out']) {
    fclose($fp);
    ...
}

$ipd = '';
do {
    // shall we check for $data === FALSE? As per the manual, it signals an error
    $ipd .= fread($fp, 32768);
    $info = stream_get_meta_data($fp);
    if ($info['timed_out']) {
        fclose($fp);
        ....
    }
} while (!feof($fp));
fclose($fp);
``` 


Tested On php 8.5.4, ubuntu noble, guzzle 7.13.2.

**Description**

Provide a method for Guzzle to capture the peers TLS certificate.

To allow the client to perform additional validation/inspection of the peers TLS certificate - in our use case we use this to raise warnings/brownouts when the certificate is close to expiration.

I'm submitting this as a feature request as Guzzle now raises a deprecation notice with our implementation of this feature.

```
User Deprecated: Since guzzlehttp/guzzle 7.12: Passing CURLOPT_CERTINFO (172) in the "curl" request option is deprecated; guzzlehttp/guzzle 8.0 will reject raw cURL options outside the built-in cURL handlers' allow-list.
```

**Example**

Example of our current usage.

```php
$client->request($uri, [
    'tls_peer_certificate' => function (string $peerCertificate) {
        $parsed = openssl_x509_parse($peerCertificate);
        // Pull out expiry...
        $this->logger->info('Peer TLS certificate expiration {expires_at}');
    },
]);
```

**Additional context**

This is how we have added support to Guzzle 7.

```php
final class CertificateCurlFactory implements CurlFactoryInterface
{
    private const OPTION = 'tls_peer_certificate';

    public function __construct(private readonly CurlFactoryInterface $decorated) {}

    public function create(RequestInterface $request, array $options): EasyHandle
    {
        if (isset($options[self::OPTION])) {
            $options['curl'][\CURLOPT_CERTINFO] = true;
        }

        return $this->decorated->create($request, $options);
    }

    public function release(EasyHandle $easy): void
    {
        if (isset($easy->options[self::OPTION])) {
            \assert(\is_object($easy->handle));

            $certinfo = \curl_getinfo($easy->handle, \CURLINFO_CERTINFO);

            if (isset($certinfo[0]['Cert'])) {
                $certificate = $certinfo[0]['Cert'];

                $easy->options[self::OPTION]($certificate);
            }
        }

        $this->decorated->release($easy);
    }
}
```

Tested on php 8.5.4 / curl 8.18.0 / ubuntu 24.04 / guzzle 7.13.1:

I have implemented a server-side endpoint that, when receiving a HEAD request, sends back a response which has a content-length header, but no body.

It is my understanding (by reading RFC9110) that this behaviour is correct, or at least acceptable, as long as the content-length communicated is the same as the response would have in case of an identical GET request.

When using Guzzle to send requests to such server endpoints, in its default configuration (ie. using Guzzle as handler), it just hangs - in short, Curl, having received the content-length header, just waits for the server to send the response body (this is confirmed by the error message gotten when adding a timeout to the guzzle client).

It is to note that both Guzzle using the stream transport, and 2 variants of the Symfony Http Client (using curl and using streams) do not show such behaviour - they just return a response.

I have managed to work around this with the following hack - but I'm not sure if this is the best fix...

```php
    if ($request->getMethod() === 'HEAD') {
        // reimplement inline `sendRequest`, with extra options for curl
        $options = [];
        $options[RequestOptions::SYNCHRONOUS] = true;
        $options[RequestOptions::ALLOW_REDIRECTS] = false;
        $options[RequestOptions::HTTP_ERRORS] = false;
        $options['curl'] = [CURLOPT_IGNORE_CONTENT_LENGTH => 1];
        return $this->guzzleClient->sendAsync($request, $options)->wait();
    }
    return $this->guzzleClient->sendRequest($request);
```

**PHP version**: 8.5.7

**Description**
We have one API client where we have to set the final base_uri via Middleware. Previously, we just left the base_uri empty and had the Middleware resolve the final.

```
    public function __invoke(callable $handler): Closure
    {
        return function(RequestInterface $request, array $options) use ($handler) {
            $configUri = new HttpFactory()->createUri($this->tenants->getFromOptions($options)->baseUrl);
            $newUri = UriResolver::resolve($configUri, $request->getUri());
            return $handler($request->withUri($newUri), $options);
        };
    }
```

When a request is sent, the buildUri() that evaluates - and checks - the URI runs before the middleware.

My first goto was to set the base_uri to "https://localhost" but this causes the URI to be resolved differently:

`$client->request('GET', 'some/path', [Tenants::TENANT_ID_OPTIONS_KEY => $tenantId]);`
Before:https://localhost/this/one/some/path
Now: https://localhost/some/path

**How to reproduce**
Middleware:
```
use GuzzleHttp\Client;
use GuzzleHttp\HandlerStack;
use GuzzleHttp\Psr7\HttpFactory;
use GuzzleHttp\Psr7\UriResolver;
use Psr\Http\Message\RequestInterface;

$stack = HandlerStack::create();
$stack->push(fn(callable $handler) => function(RequestInterface $request, array $options) use ($handler) {
    $configUri = new HttpFactory()->createUri('https://new-base-uri/');
    $newUri = UriResolver::resolve($configUri, $request->getUri());
    return $handler($request->withUri($newUri), $options);
});
$client = new Client([
    'base_uri' => 'https://localhost/this/one/',
    'handler' => $stack,
]);
$client->request('GET', 'some/path');
```

**Possible Solution**
Run the check after the middleware or allow a "trust me bro" option that disables the check

**Additional context**
We have A LOT of APIs, all require different configurations and requests, so we have a good mix of relative and absolute URLs and paths.

I downgraded to 7.12.3 which has the same "problem" when a base_uri is set. 
I tried something like `$newUri = UriResolver::resolve($configUri, $request->getUri()->withScheme('')->withHost(''));` but as soon as a base_uri is set, the path is treated absolute so the final URL changes.

I will play around with this more, advice/a solution would be much appreciated

Currently, Guzzle 8 deprecates passing native cURL options (like `CURLOPT_SSLVERSION`) via the `['curl']` request option. While Guzzle provides `RequestOptions::CRYPTO_METHOD` as an abstraction to set the TLS version, this native option only allows pinning a *specific* or minimum TLS version (e.g., `\STREAM_CRYPTO_METHOD_TLSv1_2_CLIENT`). 

There is currently no transport-agnostic way to define a **maximum TLS boundary** (equivalent to cURL's `CURL_SSLVERSION_MAX_TLSv1_2`). This is highly necessary to mitigate the infamous OpenSSL 3.0 + HTTP/2 `unexpected eof while reading, errno 0` bug, which frequently occurs in managed environments like Google App Engine. 

I propose adding a new configuration key (e.g., `RequestOptions::CRYPTO_METHOD_MAX` or extending the existing SSL/crypto abstractions) so developers can cap the TLS version cleanly without triggering Guzzle 8 deprecation warnings.

**Example**

*Before (Guzzle 7 workaround - Now deprecated in Guzzle 8):*
```php
$client = new Client([
    RequestOptions::VERSION => 2.0,
    'curl' => [
        // This will be rejected in Guzzle 8
        CURLOPT_SSLVERSION => CURL_SSLVERSION_MAX_TLSv1_2
    ]
]);

```

*After (Proposed Native Solution):*

```php
$client = new Client([
    RequestOptions::VERSION => 2.0,
    // Proposed new option
    RequestOptions::CRYPTO_METHOD_MAX => \CURL_SSLVERSION_MAX_TLSv1_2, 
    // Or alternatively, an abstraction like: RequestOptions::MAX_TLS_VERSION => '1.2'
]);

```

**Additional context**
To work around this in Guzzle 8 without triggering the `curl` option deprecation warning, developers are forced to write a custom `CurlFactoryInterface` implementation.

However, this forces user-land code to depend on Guzzle's `EasyHandle` class:

```php
public function create(RequestInterface $request, array $options): EasyHandle 
{
    $easy = $this->factory->create($request, $options);
    curl_setopt($easy->handle, \CURLOPT_SSLVERSION, \CURL_SSLVERSION_MAX_TLSv1_2);
    return $easy;
}

```

Because `EasyHandle` is marked as `@internal`, strict static analysis tools like PHPStan (level 8/9) will fail the build, forcing developers to litter their code with `@phpstan-ignore-line` comments just to set a basic TLS limitation. A native Request Option would resolve both the deprecation warnings and the static analysis conflicts.

**PHP version**: 8.4.0

**Description**
`Client` now emits a deprecation warning if you pass in `ssl_key` option with this structure `array{string,\Stringable}`.

However `CurlFactory` now strictly checks the type and throws an `InvalidArgumentException`.

**How to reproduce**

```php
declare(strict_types=1);

use GuzzleHttp\Client;

require 'vendor/autoload.php';

$secret = new class() implements \Stringable {
    public function __toString(): string
    {
        return 'my_secret';
    }
};

$client = new Client([
    'ssl_cert' => '/dev/null',
    'ssl_key' => ['/dev/null', $secret],
]);

$client->request('GET', 'http://127.0.0.1/');
```

```sh
composer require guzzlehttp/guzzle:<7.11.0
php -f test.php
# No InvalidArgumentException is thrown
```

```sh
composer require guzzlehttp/guzzle:=7.11.0
php -f test.php
# InvalidArgumentException is thrown
# PHP Fatal error:  Uncaught InvalidArgumentException: Invalid ssl_key request option in /.../vendor/guzzlehttp/guzzle/src/Handler/CurlFactory.php:976
```

**Possible Solution**

* Remove `is_string()` checks from `CurlFactory`
* Consider supporting `Stringable` types explicitly

**Additional context**

I realise this was basically undocumented, but the [docs do not](https://docs.guzzlephp.org/en/stable/request-options.html#ssl-key) specify the structure of the array.

The rationale for using an object which can be converted to string was to defend against the passphrase being disclosed in stack traces.
